<br>
     My main issue is the lack of anything like air to push off of in space making it difficult to achieve the desired aforementioned results without mass storage of secondary fuels like Hydrogen that are easily exhaustible. It may not be possible but I believe it is even if it is beyond our abilities at the moment. <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1177<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/8/02 8:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Any Ideas for nuclear propulsion.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> My main issue is the lack of anything like air to push off of in space...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I hope I've simply mis-read the above, but pushing off of something is not an issue...<br>
<br>
Newton's third law of motion. Formally stated, Newton's third law is:<br>
<br>
&quot;For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.&quot;<br>
<br>
The statement means that in every interaction, there is a pair of forces acting on the two interacting objects. The size of the forces on the first object equals the size of the force on the second object. The direction of the force on the first object is opposite to the direction of the force on the second object. Forces always come in pairs - equal and opposite action-reaction force pairs.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Does anyone have any Ideas for a way to convert nuclear Power directly to propulsion without using easily exhaustible resources in combination (ie the use of nuclear bombs in nuclear pulse rockets).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I rather like the idea behind Nuclear Pulse Propulsion, it's relatively simple, nuclear bombs appear to be fairly reliable and difficult to accidently set off.  The amount of power that is produced for the size is astronomical compared to chemical rockets.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1179<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/8/02 1:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Nuclear Space Cruiser</span><hr size=1> Ideas for using nuclear-fuel-powered interplanetary spacecraft have stirred the imaginations of designers outside of NASA. Perhaps the most ambitious plan has been offered by Fred Roth. A Florida resident, Roth has spent five years attempting to interest the Pentagon in building his massive Nuclear Space Cruiser, to protect the planet from errant asteroids and unforeseen threats.<br>
<br>
Roth's cruiser (design plans shown below) would resemble a flattened child's top. Assembled in space, it would stand 650 ft. tall and have a 9000-ft. circumference. The massive interior is needed, he says, to house a nuclear reactor and a system of ducts that function as 700 particle accelerators. &quot;The proton beams emerging out of the ship's 30-mile cyclotron accelerator system give the ship tremendous lift, direction and great velocity,&quot; he says. The reactor would also energize banks of lasers.<br>
<br>
Roth has provided the Pentagon with detailed plans, but so far there has been no official interest.<br>
<br>
