To turn electrical energy into kinetic energy for space travel. Thats the question being asked. I think the answer is no. Mechanical space drives have been purported to exist but have always proven fake. At present we cannot achieve such a thing. Ofcourse, even if we could, it would likely involve a variant form of reaction mass anyway. Just a new form of energy.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 235<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/8/02 8:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Any Ideas for nuclear propulsion.</span><hr size=1> I'll take a different interpretation of the question. Don't know if this is what was being asked, but it's an idea.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; the lack of anything like air to push off of in space making it<br>
difficult to achieve the desired aforementioned results without<br>
mass storage of secondary fuels like Hydrogen that are easily<br>
exhaustible.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 In this case, I remember a reference to the air between the pulse units and the ground launched ship acting to provide an extra kick, thereby allowing the smaller yield pulse units (Thereby making Orion one of the few air-breathing rockets which actually does use &quot;air to push against&quot; -sort of!). I think I ran across this in G.Dyson's new book, while scanning it in a store. Anybody else remember this?<br>
In this case, the lack of air in space requires &quot;exhaustible fuels like Hydrogen&quot;.<br>
 I don't see it as a problem. We've already taken a huge chunk off the fuel requirements; No longer is fuel 99+% of the ships' starting mass... Given the huge performance advantages NPR gives us, it's good enough to literally eliminate all the present difficulties in interplanetary travel.<br>
 Also, remember that we have F.Dyson saying that between 2/3 (in the new book) to 90% (in &quot;the Starship and the Canoe&quot;) of the pulse unit is propellant. Granted, this is a lot of expended mass to be carried along, but it also means that it's easily refueled in space. Lets us see the potential advantage in the perceived disadvantage of needing propellant mass.<br>
<br>
 Even ICAN uses expended propellant mass, as does NSWR.<br>
 Get around this with magnetic sails, when they can be built, though I wonder if they'll get the mass lift / high thrust capability of NPR. I do recall reading that with eventually feasible performances they can hover against strong magnetic fields, and it may be possible to lift off Earth this way.<br>
 In any near-term practical application though, they'll be strapped for mass carrying capacity. Power density of the power source must be outrageously high, as must the standards of performance of the superconductors.<br>
<br>
 There's also the flashlight engine, or Photon drive; shine a really strong photon source aft, and get the reaction of all that highly energetic reaction mass going aft at C... You must admit that photons are the ideal propellant!<br>
 Then there's the zero-point power plant and the &quot;Roswell electro-kinematic reactonless/inertia eliminating drive&quot;.<br>
 In both of these, the devil is in the details, as far as practical engineering...<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=brucetrib>brucetrib</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/9/02 7:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Any Ideas for nuclear propulsion.</span><hr size=1> If this adds to what has already been said... good question. I had run into a read on &quot;Long-life space reactor for Photon propulsion&quot; paper by Tetsu Sawada, Hiroshi Endo, Alexandre Netchaev, STAIF 2002 presentation.<br>
<br>
Apparently they have checked out the capability of rocket propulsion using photons generated by the conversion of the heat source owing to high-temperature fission reactor. &quot;The ultimate purpose is to have an insight for the possibility to realize the flights to nearby fixed star by manned spaceships&quot;<br>
<br>
Gallium-cooled liquid-metallic-fueled high-temp. fast reactor. Uh...something akin to molten Sea Salt space reactor type? Sounds good but don't these type reactors suffer from excessive corrosion?<br>
<br>
